{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496470"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:47:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:47:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1365"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1365"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.01,0.01,0.79,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72546"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1365"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58016"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"3382"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24604"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72546"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of severe upper abdominal pain and vomiting. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He drinks approximately eight standard drinks of alcohol per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 125/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. There is marked epigastric tenderness and grey-red discolouration in both flanks (Image). Blood tests reveal a lipase of 250 U/L (12-70) and mildly deranged liver function tests.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following eponymous signs best describes this bruising pattern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cullen","Fox","Bryant","Grey-Turner","Stabler"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of acute pancreatitis including severe epigastric pain, vomiting, and elevated lipase. The grey-red discolouration in the flanks is known as \u003Cstrong\u003EGrey-Turner\u0027s sign\u003C/strong\u003E, which occurs when pancreatic enzymes cause retroperitoneal hemorrhage that tracks through tissue planes to become visible at the flanks. This sign indicates severe disease and poor prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECullen\u0027s sign\u003C/strong\u003E refers to periumbilical bruising, which can also occur in severe pancreatitis due to tracking of hemorrhagic fluid through the falciform ligament to the umbilicus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFox\u0027s sign\u003C/strong\u003E describes bruising in the upper thigh region, which can occur with retroperitoneal hemorrhage but is not the pattern shown in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBryant\u0027s sign\u003C/strong\u003E refers to scrotal bruising, which can occur when retroperitoneal blood tracks down through the inguinal canal but is not demonstrated here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStabler\u0027s sign\u003C/strong\u003E describes bruising in the inguinal and pubic region, which can occur with pelvic or retroperitoneal hemorrhage but does not match the distribution shown.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile these eponymous signs are all associated with internal hemorrhage or inflammation, Grey-Turner\u0027s sign specifically describes the flank ecchymoses seen in this case. The presence of Grey-Turner\u0027s sign typically indicates severe disease and should prompt consideration for intensive care admission.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Grey-Turner\u0027s sign (flank bruising) indicates retroperitoneal hemorrhage, classically seen in severe acute pancreatitis.","Bruising patterns can help identify the anatomical source and severity of intra-abdominal pathology.","Cullen\u0027s sign (periumbilical bruising) often accompanies Grey-Turner\u0027s sign in severe pancreatitis."],"references":["Rastogi V, Singh D, Tekiner H, et al. Abdominal Physical Signs and Medical Eponyms: Physical Examination of Palpation Part 1, 1876\u20131907. Clinical Medicine \u0026 Research [Internet]. Clinical Medicine \u0026 Research; 2018;16(3-4):83\u201391. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30166497/","Wong E, Sayed-Hassen A. Grey Turner\u0027s sign in severe acute pancreatitis. Clin Case Rep. 2021 May 24;9(5):e04313. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8143275/","Sajad, Ahmad \u0026 Salati, Sajad. (2020). Retroperitoneal hemorrhage -A review of the eponymous cutaneous signs. Journal of Pakistan Association of Dermatologists. 30. 501-506. Available at: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/344489235_Retroperitoneal_hemorrhage_-A_review_of_the_eponymous_cutaneous_signs"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58016"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1365"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"11576"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"11576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/11576"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/644909b4-64f3-4697-82b8-ed839a9dedd1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app